JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand steadied against the dollar on Wednesday after selling off the day before when data showed the country sank into recession again last quarter, as market focus turned to global events.Stocks fell, with South Africa-based retail group Steinhoff International among those falling the most after it reported disappointing sales numbers despite a 13% rise in half-year operating profit.Read: Steinhoff reports rise in H1 profit, revenueThe benchmark Top-40 index fell 0.18% to 45 809.08. The wider All-share index closed 0.26% lower at 52 117.82.At 1609 GMT, the rand traded at 12.8325 per dollar, not far off its New York close of 12.8225.The currency fell more than 1% on Tuesday after data showed South Africa&#8217;s economy contracting by 0.7% in the first quarter of 2017 after shrinking 0.3% in the fourth qurter of 2016. Two consecutive quarters of contraction is considered a recession.Read: SA economy back in recession&#8220;The rand was shocked by the weak GDP figure but has settled back and, like global markets, is now waiting for tomorrow s &#8216;Super Thursday&#8217;, Rand Merchant Bank currency strategist John Cairns said.Traders globally remain cautious before Thursday&#8217;s election in Britain, which some worry may be far closer than some polls indicate, as well as the US Senate testimony of James Comey, the former FBI chief sacked by President Trump.In fixed income, the yield for the benchmark government bond due in 2026 was down 1 basis point to 8.475%. 